	publisher = {Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory},
	abstract = {Group foraging animals may change their spatial relationships in response to the resource landscape. The strength of social network ties across foraging groups could then reflect the energy balance of individual group members through their effect on foraging efficiency. Greater spear-nosed bats (Phyllostomus hastatus) live in social groups where unrelated females develop group-specific social calls, defend each other{\textquoteright}s offspring, and are hypothesized to coordinate social foraging to feed on balsa flowers. To test if social groups forage together, and if this increases foraging efficiency, we tracked 18 individuals from three social groups of P. hastatus on Isla Col{\'o}n, Panam{\'a} using high frequency GPS for 1 {\textendash} 3 days each. We found that individuals commuted alone but then joined group members in small foraging patches with high densities of flowering balsas, 25 km from their roost on the mainland. Proximity-based social network measures did not predict foraging efficiency or energy expenditure, but individuals with higher social associations spent more time outside of the cave. Individuals did not coordinate movement, but close proximity among individuals increased resting bout duration and synchrony, particularly when in the same patch. These results show that stronger social proximity associations were more closely tied to resting behavior, and indicate that factors other than increased feeding efficiency may structure network relationships of group members while foraging.Lay Summary Social foraging can increase foraging efficiency on hard-to-find food sources. Miniaturized high-frequency GPS allowed us to test this on groups of greater spear-nosed bats. We estimated food intake rates, energy expenditure, and the strength of bat social relationships. In contrast to our expectations, we did not find a relationship between bat social relationships and energy expenditure or foraging efficiency. However, bats took longer resting breaks when group members were close. Why these bats commute 25 km individually across the ocean to then forage near each other thus requires further investigation.Competing Interest StatementThe authors have declared no competing interest.},
